# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: glucose
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 1,3-Bisphosphoglycerate is the conjugate base of 1,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It is phosphorylated at the number 1 and 3 carbons.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The result of this phosphorylation gives 1,3BPG important biological properties such as the ability to donate a phosphate group to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) in order to form the energy storage molecule adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Compound C00118 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Enzyme 1.2.1.12 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Compound C00236 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Enzyme 2.7.2.3 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Compound C00197 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 1,3BPG is a macroergic metabolic intermediate in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It is created by the exergonic oxidation of the aldehyde in glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The result of this oxidation is the conversion of the aldehyde group into a carboxylic acid group which drives the formation of an acyl phosphate bond.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The latter reaction is the only step in the glycolytic pathway in which NAD+ is converted into NADH.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The formation reaction of 1,3BPG requires the presence of an enzyme called glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The high-energy acyl phosphate bond of 1,3BPG is important in respiration as it assists in the formation of ATP.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The molecule of ATP created during the following reaction is the first molecule produced during respiration.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The transfer of an inorganic phosphate from the carboxyl group on 1,3BPG to ADP to form ATP is reversible due to a low ΔG.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This is as a result of one acyl phosphate bond being cleaved whilst another is created.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This reaction is not naturally spontaneous and requires the presence of a catalyst.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This role is performed by the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] During the reaction phosphoglycerate kinase undergoes a substrate induced conformational change similar to another metabolic enzyme called hexokinase.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Because two molecules of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate are formed during glycolysis from one molecule of glucose, 1,3BPG can be said to be responsible for two of the ten molecules of ATP produced during the entire process.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Glycolysis also uses two molecules of ATP in its initial stages as a committed and irreversible step.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For this reason glycolysis is not reversible and has a net produce of 2 molecules of ATP and two of NADH.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The two molecules of NADH themselves go on to produce approximately 3 molecules of ATP each.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 1,3-BPG has a very similar role in the Calvin cycle to its role in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For this reason both reactions are said to be analogous.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] However the reaction pathway is effectively reversed.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The only other major difference between the two reactions is that NADPH is used as an electron donor in the calvin cycle whilst NAD+ is used as an electron acceptor in glycolysis.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] In this reaction cycle 1,3BPG originates from 3-phosphoglycerate and is made into glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate by the action of specific enzymes.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Contrary to the similar reactions of the glycolytic pathway, 1,3BPG in the Calvin cycle does not produce ATP but instead uses it.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For this reason it can be considered to be an irreversible and committed step in the cycle.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The outcome of this section of the cycle is an inorganic phosphate is removed from 1,3BPG as a hydrogen ion and two electrons are added to the compound+.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] In complete reverse of the glycolytic pathway reaction, the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase catalyses the reduction of the carboxyl group of 1,3BPG to form an aldehyde instead.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This reaction also releases an inorganic phosphate molecule which is subsequently used as energy for the donation of electrons from the conversion of NADPH to NADP+.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Overseeing this latter stage of the reaction is the enzyme glyceraldehyde-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] During normal metabolism in human erythrocytes, ≈19% of the 1,3BPG produced does not go any further in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It is instead shunted through the Luebering–Rapoport pathway involving the reduction of ATP in the red blood cells.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] During this alternate pathway it is made into a similar molecule called 2,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid (2,3BPG).
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 2,3BPG is used as a mechanism to oversee the efficient release of oxygen from hemoglobin.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Levels of this 1,3BPG will raise in a patient's blood when oxygen levels are low as this is one of the mechanisms of acclimatization.
[src:glucose/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Low oxygen levels trigger a rise in 1,3BPG levels which in turn raises the level of 2,3BPG which alters the efficiency of oxygen dissociation from hemoglobin.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The **1811 German Coast uprising** was a slave rebellion which occurred in the Territory of Orleans on January 8–10, 1811.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] It occurred on the east bank of the Mississippi River in the modern-day Louisiana parishes of St.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebellion was the largest of its kind in the history of the United States.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebels killed two white slave owner family members, but the confrontations with the U.S. military and local militiamen who were sent to suppress the rebellion, combined with post-trial executions, resulted in the deaths of 95 rebels.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] On January 8, between 64 and 125 slaves ignited a fight for freedom and marched from plantations in and near present-day LaPlace, Louisiana on the German Coast towards New Orleans.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] More people escaped slavery and joined them along the way, and some accounts claimed a total of 200 to 500 people escaped and participated in the rebellion.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] During their two-day, 20 mi (32 km)-long march the rebels, armed mostly with improvised weapons, burned five plantations along with several sugarhouses and crop fields.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] After a few planters were killed and others attacked, White settlers led by U.S. officials formed militia companies.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] In battle on January 10 they killed 40 to 45 of the people escaping slavery, while suffering no fatalities themselves, then hunted down and killed several other people without trial.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Over the next two weeks, White planters and U.S. officials interrogated, tried, executed, and decapitated an additional 44 people escaping slavery who had been captured.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Executions were generally by hanging or firing squad.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Heads were displayed on pikes to intimidate others.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Since 1995, the African American History Alliance of Louisiana has led an annual commemoration in January of the uprising, in which they have been joined by some descendants of participants in the revolt.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The sugar boom on what was known as Louisiana's German Coast (named for immigrants in the 1720s) began after the American Revolutionary War, while the area near New Orleans was still controlled by Spain.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] In the 1780s Jean Saint Malo, an escaped slave, established a colony of maroons in the swamps below New Orleans, which eventually led Spanish officials to send militia to capture him.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Saint Malo became a folk hero after his execution in New Orleans on June 19, 1784.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] A decade later, during the height of the French Revolution, Spanish officials discovered a slave conspiracy at Pointe Coupee (established by French settlers around 1720 between Natchez and New Orleans).
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] That slave uprising during the Easter holidays was suppressed before it came to fruition and resulted in 23 executions by hanging (with the severed heads then displayed on the road to New Orleans), and 31 additional slaves were flogged and sent to serve hard labor in other Spanish outposts.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the Haitian Revolution, planters established similar lucrative sugarcane plantations in the Gulf Coast area, resulting in a dense slave population.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] They converted from cotton and indigo plantations to sugarcane, so that by 1802, 70 sugar plantations produced over 3,000 tons annually.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some accounts claimed blacks outnumbered whites by nearly five to one by 1810, and about 90% of whites in the area enslaved people.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] More than half of those enslaved may have been born outside Louisiana, many in Africa, where various European nations established slave trading outposts and Kongo was ripped apart by civil wars.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the U.S. negotiated the Louisiana Purchase in 1803, both the Marquis de Lafayette and James Monroe declined to become the governor of the Territory of Orleans.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] President Thomas Jefferson then turned to a fellow Virginian, William C.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne, whom he appointed on an interim basis and who arrived in New Orleans with 350 volunteers and 18 boats.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne struggled with the area's diverse population, particularly because he spoke neither French nor Spanish.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The population also included a larger proportion of native Africans among the slaves than elsewhere in the U.S.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] In addition, the mixed-race Creole and French-speaking population grew markedly with refugees from Haiti (and their slaves) following the successful Haitian Revolution.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne was not used to a society with the number of free people of color that Louisiana had, but he worked to continue their role in the militia that had been established under Spanish rule.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Long-term French Creole residents complained to Washington, D.C., about Claiborne and new U.S. settlers in the territory, and wanted no part of President Jefferson's plan to pay 30,000 Americans to move into the new territory and amalgamate with the residents.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thus, by 1805, a delegation led by Jean Noël Destréhan went to Washington to complain about the "oppressive and degrading" form of the territorial government, but President Madison continued to support Claiborne, who had expressed great doubts about the planters' honesty and trustworthiness.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Lastly, Claiborne suspected that the Spanish in nearby West Florida might encourage an insurrection.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thus, he struggled to establish and maintain his authority.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] In the overall Territory of Orleans, from 1803 to 1811, the free black population nearly tripled, to 5,000, with 3,000 arriving as migrants from Haiti (via Cuba) in 1809–1810.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] In Saint-Domingue they had enjoyed certain rights as *gens de couleur*, including owning slaves themselves.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Furthermore, between 1790 and 1810, slave traders brought around 20,000 enslaved Africans to New Orleans.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The masters and slaves were virtually all Catholic.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The waterways and bayous around New Orleans and Lake Pontchartrain made transportation and trade possible but also provided easy escapes and nearly impenetrable hiding places for runaway slaves.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some maroon colonies continued for years within several miles of New Orleans.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] With the spread of ideas of freedom from the French and Haitian Revolutions, European Americans worried about slave uprisings, particularly in the Louisiana area.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 1805, they heard a traveling Frenchman was preaching about liberty, equality, and fraternity to the French-speaking slaves, and arrested him as dangerous.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] A group of slaves met on January 6, 1811.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] It was a period when work had relaxed on the plantations after the fierce weeks of the sugar harvest and processing.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] As planter James Brown testified weeks later, "The black Quamana [Kwamena, meaning "born on Saturday"], owned by Mr.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Brown, and the mulatto Harry, owned by Messrs.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Kenner and Henderson, were at the home of Manuel Andry on the night of Saturday–Sunday of the current month in order to deliberate with the mulatto Charles Deslondes, chief of the brigands." Slaves had spread word of the planned uprising among the slaves at plantations up and down the German Coast.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The revolt began on January 8 at the Andry plantation.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] After striking and badly wounding Andry, the slaves killed his son Gilbert.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] "An attempt was made to assassinate me by the stroke of an axe", Andry wrote.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] "My poor son has been ferociously murdered by a horde of brigands who from my plantation to that of Mr.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The approximately 15 slaves at Andry's plantation, about 30 miles (50 km) upriver from New Orleans, joined another eight slaves from the next-door plantation of the widows of Jacques and Georges Deslondes.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] This was the home plantation of Charles Deslondes, a slave driver (a slave overseer of other slaves) later described by one of the captured slaves as the "principal chief of the brigands".
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Small groups of slaves joined from every plantation the rebels passed.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Witnesses remarked on their organized march.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] They carried mostly pikes, hoes, and axes, but few firearms, and they marched to drums while some carried flags.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Approximately 10–25% of any given plantation's slave population joined with them.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] At the plantation of James Brown, Kook, one of the most active participants and key figures in the story of the uprising, joined the insurrection.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] At the next plantation down, Kook attacked and killed François Trépagnier with an axe.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] He was the second and last planter killed in the rebellion.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the band of slaves passed the LaBranche plantation, they stopped at the home of the local physician.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Finding him gone, Kook set his house on fire.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some planters testified at the trials in parish courts that they were warned by slaves of the uprising.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Others regularly stayed in New Orleans, where many had town houses, and trusted their plantations to overseers to run.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Planters quickly crossed the Mississippi River to escape the insurrection and to raise a militia.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] As those escaping moved downriver, they passed larger plantations, from which other slaves joined them.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Numerous slaves joined the insurrection from the Meuillion plantation, the largest and wealthiest plantation on the German Coast.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebels laid waste to Meuillion's house.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] They tried to set it on fire, but a slave named Bazile fought the fire and saved the house.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising started in present-day LaPlace and followed a 20-mile trek on the old River Road through the present-day towns of Montz, Norco, New Sarpy, Destrehan, St.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Rose and ended at much of what had once been the Kenner and Henderson Plantations and is now Rivertown and Louis Armstrong International Airport in Kenner.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] After nightfall the escaping slaves reached Cannes-Brulées, about 15 miles (24 km) northwest of New Orleans.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The men had traveled between 14 and 22 miles (23 and 35 km), a march that probably took them seven to ten hours.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] By some accounts, they numbered "some 200 slaves", although other accounts estimated up to 500.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] As typical of revolts of most classes, free or slave, the insurgent slaves were mostly young men between the ages of 20 and 30.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] They represented primarily lower-skilled occupations on the sugar plantations, where slaves labored in difficult conditions with a low life expectancy.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Despite his injuries, Andry crossed the river and made contact with other planters, raising a militia and pursuing the escaping slaves.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] By noon on January 9, the residents of New Orleans had heard about the insurrection.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] By sunset, General Wade Hampton I, Commodore John Shaw, and Claiborne sent two volunteer militia companies, 30 US Army soldiers, and 40 US Navy sailors to fight the escaping slaves.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] By about 4 a.m. on January 10, this force had reached Jacques Fortier's plantation, where Hampton thought the escaped slaves had encamped overnight.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] However, the escaped slaves had started back upriver about two hours earlier, had traveled about 15 miles (24 km) back up the coast, and had neared Bernard Bernoudy's plantation.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] There, planter Charles Perret, in cooperation with Andry and Judge St.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Martin, had assembled a militia of about 80 men from the river's opposite side.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] At about 9 o'clock, this militia force discovered escaping slaves moving toward high ground on Bernoudy's plantation.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Perret ordered his men to attack the escaping slaves, which he later wrote numbered about 200 men, about half on horseback.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] (Most accounts said only the leaders were mounted, and historians believe it unlikely the escaping men could have gathered so many mounts.) Within a half-hour, 40 to 45 escaping people had been killed; the remainder slipped away into the woods and swamps.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Perret's and Andry's militias tried to pursue them despite the difficult terrain.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] On January 11, the militia, assisted by Native American trackers as well as hunting dogs, captured Deslondes, whom Andry considered "the principal leader of the bandits." A slave driver and son of a white man and a slave, Deslondes received no trial or interrogation.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The following day Pierre Griffee and Hans Wimprenn, who were thought the murderers of M.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] François Trépagnier, were captured, killed, and their heads decapitated for delivery to the Andry estate.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Major Milton and the dragoons from Baton Rouge arrived and provided support for the militia, since Hampton believed them supported by Spanish authorities in West Florida.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Having suppressed the insurrection, the planters and government officials continued to search for people who had escaped.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Those captured later were interrogated and jailed before trials.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Officials convened three tribunals: one at Destrehan Plantation in St.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] John the Baptist Parish, and the third in New Orleans (Orleans Parish).
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The Destrehan trials, overseen by Judge Pierre Bauchet St.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Martin, resulted in the execution of 18 of 21 captured people by firing squad.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some slaves testified against others, but others refused to testify or submit to the all-planter tribunal.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] In New Orleans, Commodore Shaw presumed that "but few of those who have been taken were acquitted." The New Orleans trials resulted in the conviction and summary executions of 11 more slaves.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Three were publicly hanged in the *Place d'Armes*, now Jackson Square.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] One of those spared was a 13-year-old boy, who was ordered to witness another man's death and then received 30 lashes.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Another escaped person was treated with leniency because his uncle turned him in and begged for mercy.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The sentence of a third person was commuted because of the valuable information he had given.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The heads of those executed were put on pikes and the mutilated bodies of dead rebels displayed to intimidate other slaves.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The naval officer Samuel Hambleton described the heads posted on stakes that lined the levee as follows, "They were brung up here for the sake of their Heads, which decorate our Levee, all the way up the coast.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] U.S. territorial law provided no appeal from a parish court's ruling, even in cases involving imposition of a death sentence on a slave.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] In fact, Claiborne did commute two death sentences, those of Henry and Theodore, each referred by the Orleans Parish court.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] No record has been found of any referral from the court in St.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Charles Parish, or of any refusal by the governor of an application for clemency.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Militias killed about 95 slaves between the battle, subsequent summary apprehensions and executions, as well as by execution after trials.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] From the trial records, most of the leaders appeared to have been mixed-race Creoles or mulattoes, although numerous slaves were native-born Africans.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Fifty-six of the slaves captured on January 10 and involved in the revolt were returned to their masters, who may have punished them but wanted their valuable laborers back to work.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thirty more escaping slaves were captured and returned to their masters after planters determined they had been forced to join the revolt by Deslondes and his men.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The heirs of Meuillon petitioned the legislature for permission to free the mulatto slave Bazile, who had worked to preserve his master's plantation.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Not all the slaves supported insurrection, knowing the trouble it could bring and not wanting to see their homes and communities destroyed.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising was short-lived and quickly crushed by local authorities.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Showing planter influence, the legislature of the Territory of Orleans approved compensation of $300 to planters for each escaping slave killed or executed.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The territory gratefully accepted the presence of U.S. troops after the revolt.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The national press covered the insurrection, with some Northerners seeing it arising out of the wrongs suffered under slavery.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] Since 1995, the African American History Alliance of Louisiana has led an annual commemoration at Norco in January, where they have been joined by some descendants of members of the revolt.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] While the Destrehan Plantation tour concentrates on architecture and white lifestyle and family histories, a small museum in a converted slave cabin (not on the standard tour) features folk paintings of the 1811 uprising.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] More recently, the Whitney Plantation, in St.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] John the Baptist Parish, opened in 2014 and is the first plantation museum in the country dedicated to the slave experience.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The Whitney Plantation includes a memorial and information to commemorate the 1811 Slave Uprising of the German Coast.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 2015, artist Dread Scott began organizing a massive re-enactment of the uprising; the 26 mile, 2-day event took place in November 2019.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising is featured in Talene Monahon's 2020 play about historical reenactment, *How to Load a Musket*.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 2021, the 1811 Kid Ory Historic House opened on the site of Woodland Plantation in LaPlace, which is in the National Register of Historic Places of the United States.
[src:glucose/1811-german-coast-uprising] The museum is dedicated to the German Coast uprising and to Kid Ory, an American jazz composer, trombonist, and bandleader born there in 1886.
[src:glucose/2-deoxy-d-glucose] 2-DG is up taken by the glucose transporters of the cell.
[src:glucose/2-deoxy-d-glucose] Therefore, cells with higher glucose uptake, for example tumor cells, have also a higher uptake of 2-DG.
[src:glucose/2-deoxy-d-glucose] Since 2-DG hampers cell growth, its use as a tumor therapeutic has been suggested, and in fact, 2-DG is in clinical trials.
[src:glucose/2-deoxy-d-glucose] It is not completely clear how 2-DG inhibits cell growth.
[src:glucose/2-deoxy-d-glucose] The fact that glycolysis is inhibited by 2-DG, seems not to be sufficient to explain why 2-DG treated cells stop growing.
[src:glucose/2-deoxy-d-glucose] A synergistic effect between 2-DG and various other agents have been reported in the pursuit of anticancer strategies.
[src:glucose/2-deoxy-d-glucose] Because of its structural similarity to mannose, 2DG has the potential to inhibit N-glycosylation in mammalian cells and other systems, and as such induces ER stress and the Unfolded Protein Response (UPR) pathway.
[src:glucose/2-deoxy-d-glucose] 2-DG has been used as a targeted optical imaging agent for fluorescent *in vivo* imaging.
[src:glucose/2-deoxy-d-glucose] In clinical medical imaging (PET scanning), fluorodeoxyglucose is used, where one of the 2-hydrogens of 2-deoxy-D-glucose is replaced with the positron-emitting isotope fluorine-18, which emits paired gamma rays, allowing distribution of the tracer to be imaged by external gamma camera(s).
[src:glucose/2-deoxy-d-glucose] This is increasingly done in tandem with a CT function which is part of the same PET/CT machine, to allow better localization of small-volume tissue glucose-uptake differences.
[src:glucose/2-deoxy-d-glucose] On May 8, 2021, the Drugs Controller General of India approved an oral formulation of 2-deoxy-D-glucose for emergency use as adjunct therapy in moderate to severe coronavirus patients.
[src:glucose/2-deoxy-d-glucose] The drug was developed by the DRDO along with Dr.
[src:glucose/2-deoxy-d-glucose] Reddy's Laboratories, who jointly claimed via a press release, that the drug "helps in faster recovery of hospitalised patients and reduces supplemental oxygen dependence".
[src:glucose/2-deoxy-d-glucose] The Wire as well as The Hindu noted that the approval was based on poor evidence; no journal publication (or preprint) concerning efficacy and safety are yet available.
[src:glucose/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] 2-phosphoglyceric acid is an intermediate that is part of the glycolysis pathway, and it is converted into phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) by an enolase.
[src:glucose/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] There are three types of enolase enzymes that are able to catalyze the conversion of 2-phosphoglyceric acid into PEP, which are alpha-enolase, beta-enolase, and gamma-enolase.
[src:glucose/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Studies have found that Alpha-enolase is the most common enolase, so it is often the specific enolase used to convert 2-phosphoglyceric acid into PEP.
[src:glucose/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Alpha-enolase catalyzes this conversion process by acting as a Hydrolase, which means that alpha-enolase removes a water molecule from the 2-phosphoglyceric acid in order to form PEP.
[src:glucose/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 5.4.2.1 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:glucose/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00631 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:glucose/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 4.2.1.11 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:glucose/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00074 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:glucose/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the glycolytic pathway, 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate is dephosphorylated to form 3-phosphoglyceric acid in a coupled reaction producing two ATP via substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:glucose/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] The single phosphate group left on the 3-PGA molecule then moves from an end carbon to a central carbon, producing 2-phosphoglycerate.
[src:glucose/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This phosphate group relocation is catalyzed by phosphoglycerate mutase, an enzyme that also catalyzes the reverse reaction.
[src:glucose/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the light-independent reactions (also known as the Calvin-Benson cycle), two 3-phosphoglycerate molecules are synthesized.
[src:glucose/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] RuBP, a 5-carbon sugar, undergoes carbon fixation, catalyzed by the rubisco enzyme, to become an unstable 6-carbon intermediate.
[src:glucose/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This intermediate is then cleaved into two, separate 3-carbon molecules of 3-PGA.
[src:glucose/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] G3P eventually reacts to form the sugars such as glucose or fructose or more complex starches.
[src:glucose/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Glycerate 3-phosphate (formed from 3-phosphoglycerate) is also a precursor for serine, which, in turn, can create cysteine and glycine through the homocysteine cycle.
[src:glucose/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] 3-phosphoglycerate can be separated and measured using paper chromatography as well as with column chromatography and other chromatographic separation methods.
[src:glucose/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] It can be identified using both gas-chromatography and liquid-chromatography mass spectrometry and has been optimized for evaluation using tandem MS techniques.
[src:glucose/glucose] In energy metabolism, glucose is the most important source of energy in all organisms.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose for metabolism is stored as a polymer, in plants mainly as amylose and amylopectin, and in animals as glycogen.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose circulates in the blood of animals as blood sugar.
[src:glucose/glucose] The naturally occurring form is d-glucose, while its stereoisomer l-glucose is produced synthetically in comparatively small amounts and is less biologically active.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose is a monosaccharide containing six carbon atoms and an aldehyde group, and is therefore an aldohexose.
[src:glucose/glucose] The glucose molecule can exist in an open-chain (acyclic) as well as ring (cyclic) form.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose is naturally occurring and is found in its free state in fruits and other parts of plants.
[src:glucose/glucose] In animals, it is released from the breakdown of glycogen in a process known as glycogenolysis.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose, as intravenous sugar solution, is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:glucose/glucose] It is also on the list in combination with sodium chloride (table salt).
[src:glucose/glucose] The name glucose is derived from Ancient Greek γλεῦκος (*gleûkos*) 'wine, must', from γλυκύς (*glykýs*) 'sweet'.
[src:glucose/glucose] The suffix *-ose* is a chemical classifier denoting a sugar.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose was first isolated from raisins in 1747 by the German chemist Andreas Marggraf.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose was discovered in grapes by another German chemist, Johann Tobias Lowitz, in 1792, and distinguished as being different from cane sugar (sucrose).
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose is the term coined by Jean-Baptiste Dumas in 1838, which has prevailed in the chemical literature.
[src:glucose/glucose] Friedrich August Kekulé proposed the term **dextrose** (from the Latin *dexter*, meaning "right"), because in aqueous solutions of glucose, the plane of linearly polarized light is turned to the right.
[src:glucose/glucose] In contrast, l-fructose (usually referred to as d-fructose) (a ketohexose) and l-glucose (l-glucose) turn linearly polarized light to the left.
[src:glucose/glucose] Since glucose is a basic necessity of many organisms, a correct understanding of its chemical makeup and structure contributed greatly to a general advancement in organic chemistry.
[src:glucose/glucose] This understanding occurred largely as a result of the investigations of Hermann Emil Fischer, a German chemist who received the 1902 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for his findings.
[src:glucose/glucose] The synthesis of glucose established the structure of organic material and consequently formed the first definitive validation of Jacobus Henricus van 't Hoff's theories of chemical kinetics and the arrangements of chemical bonds in carbon-bearing molecules.
[src:glucose/glucose] Between 1891 and 1894, Fischer established the stereochemical configuration of all the known sugars and correctly predicted the possible isomers, applying the Van 't Hoff equation of asymmetrical carbon atoms.
[src:glucose/glucose] The names initially referred to the natural substances.
[src:glucose/glucose] Their enantiomers were given the same name with the introduction of systematic nomenclatures, taking into account absolute stereochemistry (e.g.
[src:glucose/glucose] Fischer nomenclature, d/l nomenclature).
[src:glucose/glucose] For the discovery of the metabolism of glucose Otto Fritz Meyerhof received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1922.
[src:glucose/glucose] Hans von Euler-Chelpin was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry along with Arthur Harden in 1929 for their "research on the fermentation of sugar and their share of enzymes in this process".
[src:glucose/glucose] In 1947, Bernardo Houssay (for his discovery of the role of the pituitary gland in the metabolism of glucose and the derived carbohydrates) as well as Carl and Gerty Cori (for their discovery of the conversion of glycogen from glucose) received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:glucose/glucose] In 1970, Luis Leloir was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for the discovery of glucose-derived sugar nucleotides in the biosynthesis of carbohydrates.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose forms white or colorless solids that are highly soluble in water and acetic acid but poorly soluble in methanol and ethanol.
[src:glucose/glucose] They melt at 146 °C (295 °F) (*α*) and 150 °C (302 °F) (*beta*), decompose starting at 188 °C (370 °F) with release of various volatile products, ultimately leaving a residue of carbon.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose has a pKa value of 12.16 at 25 °C (77 °F) in water.
[src:glucose/glucose] With six carbon atoms, it is classed as a hexose, a subcategory of the monosaccharides. d-Glucose is one of the sixteen aldohexose stereoisomers.
[src:glucose/glucose] The d-isomer, d-glucose, also known as dextrose, occurs widely in nature, but the l-isomer, l-glucose, does not.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose can be obtained by hydrolysis of carbohydrates such as milk sugar (lactose), cane sugar (sucrose), maltose, cellulose, glycogen, etc.
[src:glucose/glucose] Dextrose is commonly commercially manufactured from starches, such as corn starch in the US and Japan, from potato and wheat starch in Europe, and from tapioca starch in tropical areas.
[src:glucose/glucose] The manufacturing process uses hydrolysis via pressurized steaming at controlled pH in a jet followed by further enzymatic depolymerization.
[src:glucose/glucose] Unbonded glucose is one of the main ingredients of honey.
[src:glucose/glucose] Anhydrous dextrose has the chemical formula C6H12O6, without any water molecule attached which is the same as glucose.
[src:glucose/glucose] Anhydrous dextrose on open air tends to absorb moisture and transform to the monohydrate, and it is more expensive to produce.
[src:glucose/glucose] Anhydrous dextrose (anhydrous D-glucose) has increased stability and increased shelf life, has medical applications, such as in oral glucose tolerance test.
[src:glucose/glucose] Whereas molecular weight (molar mass) for D-glucose monohydrate is 198.17 g/mol, that for anhydrous D-glucose is 180.16 g/mol The density of these two forms of glucose is also different.
[src:glucose/glucose] In terms of chemical structure, glucose is a monosaccharide, that is, a simple sugar.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose contains six carbon atoms and an aldehyde group, and is therefore an aldohexose.
[src:glucose/glucose] The glucose molecule can exist in an open-chain (acyclic) as well as ring (cyclic) form—due to the presence of alcohol and aldehyde or ketone functional groups, the form having the straight chain can easily convert into a chair-like hemiacetal ring structure commonly found in carbohydrates.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose is present in solid form as a monohydrate with a closed pyran ring (α-D-glucopyranose monohydrate, sometimes known less precisely by dextrose hydrate).
[src:glucose/glucose] In aqueous solution, on the other hand, a small proportion of glucose can be found in an open-chain configuration while remaining predominantly as α- or β-pyranose, which interconvert.
[src:glucose/glucose] From aqueous solutions, the three known forms can be crystallized: α-glucopyranose, β-glucopyranose and α-glucopyranose monohydrate.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose is a building block of the disaccharides lactose and sucrose (cane or beet sugar), of oligosaccharides such as raffinose and of polysaccharides such as starch, amylopectin, glycogen, and cellulose.
[src:glucose/glucose] The glass transition temperature of glucose is 31 °C (88 °F) and the Gordon–Taylor constant (an experimentally determined constant for the prediction of the glass transition temperature for different mass fractions of a mixture of two substances) is 4.5.
[src:glucose/glucose] An open-chain form of glucose makes up less than 0.02% of the glucose molecules in an aqueous solution at equilibrium.
[src:glucose/glucose] The rest is one of two cyclic hemiacetal forms.
[src:glucose/glucose] In its open-chain form, the glucose molecule has an open (as opposed to cyclic) unbranched backbone of six carbon atoms, where C-1 is part of an aldehyde group H(C=O)−.
[src:glucose/glucose] Therefore, glucose is also classified as an aldose, or an aldohexose.
[src:glucose/glucose] The aldehyde group makes glucose a reducing sugar giving a positive reaction with the Fehling test.
[src:glucose/glucose] In solutions, the open-chain form of glucose (either "D-" or "L-") exists in equilibrium with several cyclic isomers, each containing a ring of carbons closed by one oxygen atom.
[src:glucose/glucose] In aqueous solution, however, more than 99% of glucose molecules exist as pyranose forms.
[src:glucose/glucose] The open-chain form is limited to about 0.25%, and furanose forms exist in negligible amounts.
[src:glucose/glucose] The terms "glucose" and "D-glucose" are generally used for these cyclic forms as well.
[src:glucose/glucose] The ring arises from the open-chain form by an intramolecular nucleophilic addition reaction between the aldehyde group (at C-1) and either the C-4 or C-5 hydroxyl group, forming a hemiacetal linkage, −C(OH)H−O−.
[src:glucose/glucose] The reaction between C-1 and C-5 yields a six-membered heterocyclic system called a pyranose, which is a monosaccharide sugar (hence "-ose") containing a derivatised pyran skeleton.
[src:glucose/glucose] The (much rarer) reaction between C-1 and C-4 yields a five-membered furanose ring, named after the cyclic ether furan.
[src:glucose/glucose] In either case, each carbon in the ring has one hydrogen and one hydroxyl attached, except for the last carbon (C-4 or C-5) where the hydroxyl is replaced by the remainder of the open molecule (which is −(C(CH2OH)HOH)−H or −(CHOH)−H respectively).
[src:glucose/glucose] The ring-closing reaction can give two products, denoted "α-" and "β-".
[src:glucose/glucose] Therefore, the open-chain isomer D-glucose gives rise to four distinct cyclic isomers: α-D-glucopyranose, β-D-glucopyranose, α-D-glucofuranose, and β-D-glucofuranose.
[src:glucose/glucose] These five structures exist in equilibrium and interconvert, and the interconversion is much more rapid with acid catalysis.
[src:glucose/glucose] The other open-chain isomer L-glucose similarly gives rise to four distinct cyclic forms of L-glucose, each the mirror image of the corresponding D-glucose.
[src:glucose/glucose] The glucopyranose ring (α or β) can assume several non-planar shapes, analogous to the "chair" and "boat" conformations of cyclohexane.
[src:glucose/glucose] Similarly, the glucofuranose ring may assume several shapes, analogous to the "envelope" conformations of cyclopentane.
[src:glucose/glucose] In the solid state, only the glucopyranose forms are observed.
[src:glucose/glucose] Some derivatives of glucofuranose, such as 1,2-*O*-isopropylidene-D-glucofuranose are stable and can be obtained pure as crystalline solids.
[src:glucose/glucose] For example, reaction of α-D-glucose with *para*-tolylboronic acid H3C−(C6H4)−B(OH)2 reforms the normal pyranose ring to yield the 4-fold ester α-D-glucofuranose-1,2:3,5-bis(*p*-tolylboronate).
[src:glucose/glucose] Mutarotation consists of a temporary reversal of the ring-forming reaction, resulting in the open-chain form, followed by a reforming of the ring.
[src:glucose/glucose] The ring closure step may use a different −OH group than the one recreated by the opening step (thus switching between pyranose and furanose forms), or the new hemiacetal group created on C-1 may have the same or opposite handedness as the original one (thus switching between the α and β forms).
[src:glucose/glucose] Thus, though the open-chain form is barely detectable in solution, it is an essential component of the equilibrium.
[src:glucose/glucose] The open-chain form is thermodynamically unstable, and it spontaneously isomerizes to the cyclic forms.
[src:glucose/glucose] (Although the ring closure reaction could in theory create four- or three-atom rings, these would be highly strained, and are not observed in practice.) In solutions at room temperature, the four cyclic isomers interconvert over a time scale of hours, in a process called mutarotation.
[src:glucose/glucose] Starting from any proportions, the mixture converges to a stable ratio of α:β 36:64.
[src:glucose/glucose] The ratio would be α:β 11:89 if it were not for the influence of the anomeric effect.
[src:glucose/glucose] Mutarotation is considerably slower at temperatures close to 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:glucose/glucose] Whether in water or the solid form, d-(+)-glucose is dextrorotatory, meaning it will rotate the direction of polarized light clockwise as seen looking toward the light source.
[src:glucose/glucose] The effect is due to the chirality of the molecules, and indeed the mirror-image isomer, l-(−)-glucose, is levorotatory (rotates polarized light counterclockwise) by the same amount.
[src:glucose/glucose] The strength of the effect is different for each of the five tautomers.
[src:glucose/glucose] The d- prefix does not refer directly to the optical properties of the compound.
[src:glucose/glucose] It indicates that the C-5 chiral centre has the same handedness as that of d-glyceraldehyde (which was so labelled because it is dextrorotatory).
[src:glucose/glucose] The fact that d-glucose is dextrorotatory is a combined effect of its four chiral centres, not just of C-5; some of the other d-aldohexoses are levorotatory.
[src:glucose/glucose] The conversion between the two anomers can be observed in a polarimeter since pure α-d-glucose has a specific rotation angle of +112.2° mL/(dm·g), pure β-d-glucose of +17.5° mL/(dm·g).
[src:glucose/glucose] When equilibrium has been reached after a certain time due to mutarotation, the angle of rotation is +52.7° mL/(dm·g).
[src:glucose/glucose] By adding acid or base, this transformation is much accelerated.
[src:glucose/glucose] The equilibration takes place via the open-chain aldehyde form.
[src:glucose/glucose] In dilute sodium hydroxide or other dilute bases, the monosaccharides mannose, glucose, and fructose interconvert (via a Lobry de Bruyn–Alberda–Van Ekenstein transformation), so that a balance between these isomers is formed.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose is the most abundant monosaccharide.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose is also the most widely used aldohexose in most living organisms.
[src:glucose/glucose] One possible explanation for this is that glucose has a lower tendency than other aldohexoses to react nonspecifically with the amine groups of proteins.
[src:glucose/glucose] This reaction—glycation—impairs or destroys the function of many proteins, e.g. in glycated hemoglobin.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose's low rate of glycation can be attributed to its having a more stable cyclic form compared to other aldohexoses, which means it spends less time than they do in its reactive open-chain form.
[src:glucose/glucose] The reason for glucose having the most stable cyclic form of all the aldohexoses is that its hydroxy groups (with the exception of the hydroxy group on the anomeric carbon of d-glucose) are in the equatorial position.
[src:glucose/glucose] Presumably, glucose is the most abundant natural monosaccharide because it is less glycated with proteins than other monosaccharides.
[src:glucose/glucose] Another hypothesis is that glucose, being the only d-aldohexose that has all five hydroxy substituents in the equatorial position in the form of β-d-glucose, is more readily accessible to chemical reactions, for example, for esterification or acetal formation.
[src:glucose/glucose] For this reason, d-glucose is also a highly preferred building block in natural polysaccharides (glycans).
[src:glucose/glucose] Polysaccharides that are composed solely of glucose are termed glucans.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose is produced by plants through photosynthesis using sunlight, water, and carbon dioxide, and can be used by all living organisms as an energy and carbon source.
[src:glucose/glucose] However, most glucose does not occur in its free form, but in the form of its polymers (polysaccharides), such as sucrose and starch commonly found in plants, lactose in milk, cellulose from plant cell wall, and chitin from arthropods.
[src:glucose/glucose] These polymers, when consumed by animals, fungi, and bacteria, are degraded to glucose using enzymes.
[src:glucose/glucose] All animals are also able to produce glucose themselves from certain precursors as the need arises.
[src:glucose/glucose] Neurons, cells of the renal medulla, and erythrocytes depend on glucose for their energy production.
[src:glucose/glucose] In adult humans, there is about 18 g (0.63 oz) of glucose, of which about 4 g (0.14 oz) is present in the blood.
[src:glucose/glucose] Approximately 180–220 g (6.3–7.8 oz) of glucose is produced in the liver of an adult in 24 hours.
[src:glucose/glucose] Many of the long-term complications of diabetes (e.g., blindness, kidney failure, and peripheral neuropathy) are probably due to the glycation of proteins or lipids.
[src:glucose/glucose] In contrast, enzyme-regulated addition of sugars to protein is called glycosylation and is essential for the function of many proteins.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose binds to the taste receptor for sweetness on the human tongue, specifically, the proteins T1R2 and T1R3, thus allowing human to identify glucose-containing food sources.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose mainly comes from food—about 300 g (11 oz) per day is produced by conversion of food, but it is also synthesized from other metabolites in the body's cells.
[src:glucose/glucose] In humans, the breakdown of glucose-containing polysaccharides happens in part already during chewing by means of amylase, which is contained in saliva, as well as by maltase, lactase, and sucrase on the brush border of the small intestine.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose is a building block of many carbohydrates and can be split off from them using certain enzymes.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucosidases, a subgroup of the glycosidases, first catalyze the hydrolysis of long-chain glucose-containing polysaccharides, removing terminal glucose.
[src:glucose/glucose] In turn, disaccharides are mostly degraded by specific glycosidases to glucose.
[src:glucose/glucose] The names of the degrading enzymes are often derived from the particular poly- and disaccharide; inter alia, for the degradation of polysaccharide chains there are amylases (named after amylose, a component of starch), cellulases (named after cellulose), chitinases (named after chitin), and more.
[src:glucose/glucose] Furthermore, for the cleavage of disaccharides, there are maltase, lactase, sucrase, trehalase, and others.
[src:glucose/glucose] In humans, about 70 genes are known that code for glycosidases.
[src:glucose/glucose] They have functions in the digestion and degradation of glycogen, sphingolipids, mucopolysaccharides, and poly (ADP-ribose) polymerases.
[src:glucose/glucose] Humans do not produce cellulases, chitinases, or trehalases, but the bacteria in the gut microbiota do.
[src:glucose/glucose] In order to get into or out of cell membranes of cells and membranes of cell compartments, glucose requires special transport proteins from the major facilitator superfamily.
[src:glucose/glucose] In the small intestine (more precisely, in the jejunum), glucose is taken up into the intestinal epithelium with the help of glucose transporters via a secondary active transport mechanism called sodium ion-glucose symport via sodium/glucose cotransporter 1 (SGLT1).
[src:glucose/glucose] Further transfer occurs on the basolateral side of the intestinal epithelial cells via the glucose transporter GLUT2, as well uptake into liver cells, kidney cells, cells of the islets of Langerhans, neurons, astrocytes, and tanycytes.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose enters the liver via the portal vein and is stored there as a cellular glycogen.
[src:glucose/glucose] In the liver cell, it is phosphorylated by glucokinase at position 6 to form glucose 6-phosphate, which cannot leave the cell.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose 6-phosphatase can convert glucose 6-phosphate back into glucose exclusively in the liver, so the body can maintain a sufficient blood glucose concentration.
[src:glucose/glucose] In other cells, uptake happens by passive transport through one of the 14 GLUT proteins.
[src:glucose/glucose] In the other cell types, phosphorylation occurs through a hexokinase, whereupon glucose can no longer diffuse out of the cell.
[src:glucose/glucose] The glucose transporter GLUT1 is produced by most cell types and is of particular importance for nerve cells and pancreatic β-cells.
[src:glucose/glucose] GLUT3 is highly expressed in nerve cells.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose from the bloodstream is taken up by GLUT4 from muscle cells (of the skeletal muscle and heart muscle) and fat cells.
[src:glucose/glucose] GLUT14 is expressed exclusively in testicles.
[src:glucose/glucose] Excess glucose is broken down and converted into fatty acids, which are stored as triglycerides.
[src:glucose/glucose] In the kidneys, glucose in the urine is absorbed via SGLT1 and SGLT2 in the apical cell membranes and transmitted via GLUT2 in the basolateral cell membranes.
[src:glucose/glucose] About 90% of kidney glucose reabsorption is via SGLT2 and about 3% via SGLT1.
[src:glucose/glucose] In plants and some prokaryotes, glucose is a product of photosynthesis.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose is also formed by the breakdown of polymeric forms of glucose like glycogen (in animals and mushrooms) or starch (in plants).
[src:glucose/glucose] The cleavage of glycogen is termed glycogenolysis, the cleavage of starch is called starch degradation.
[src:glucose/glucose] The metabolic pathway that begins with molecules containing two to four carbon atoms (C) and ends in the glucose molecule containing six carbon atoms is called gluconeogenesis and occurs in all living organisms.
[src:glucose/glucose] The smaller starting materials are the result of other metabolic pathways.
[src:glucose/glucose] Ultimately almost all biomolecules come from the assimilation of carbon dioxide in plants and microbes during photosynthesis.
[src:glucose/glucose] The free energy of formation of α-d-glucose is 917.2 kilojoules per mole.
[src:glucose/glucose] In humans, gluconeogenesis occurs in the liver and kidney, but also in other cell types.
[src:glucose/glucose] In the liver about 150 g (5.3 oz) of glycogen are stored, in skeletal muscle about 250 g (8.8 oz).
[src:glucose/glucose] However, the glucose released in muscle cells upon cleavage of the glycogen can not be delivered to the circulation because glucose is phosphorylated by the hexokinase, and a glucose-6-phosphatase is not expressed to remove the phosphate group.
[src:glucose/glucose] Unlike for glucose, there is no transport protein for glucose-6-phosphate.
[src:glucose/glucose] Gluconeogenesis allows the organism to build up glucose from other metabolites, including lactate or certain amino acids, while consuming energy.
[src:glucose/glucose] The renal tubular cells can also produce glucose.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose also can be found outside of living organisms in the ambient environment.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose concentrations in the atmosphere are detected via collection of samples by aircraft and are known to vary from location to location.
[src:glucose/glucose] For example, glucose concentrations in atmospheric air ranges from 0.8 to 20.1 pg/L in inland China, to 10.3 to 142 pg/L in East coastal China.
[src:glucose/glucose] In humans, glucose is metabolized by glycolysis and the pentose phosphate pathway.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glycolysis is used by all living organisms, with small variations, and all organisms generate energy from the breakdown of monosaccharides.
[src:glucose/glucose] In the further course of the metabolism, it can be completely degraded via oxidative decarboxylation, the citric acid cycle (synonym *Krebs cycle*) and the respiratory chain to water and carbon dioxide.
[src:glucose/glucose] If there is not enough oxygen available for this, the glucose degradation in animals occurs anaerobic to lactate via lactic acid fermentation and releases much less energy.
[src:glucose/glucose] Muscular lactate enters the liver through the bloodstream in mammals, where gluconeogenesis occurs (Cori cycle).
[src:glucose/glucose] With a high supply of glucose, the metabolite acetyl-CoA from the Krebs cycle can also be used for fatty acid synthesis.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose is also used to replenish the body's glycogen stores, which are mainly found in liver and skeletal muscle.
[src:glucose/glucose] These processes are hormonally regulated.
[src:glucose/glucose] In other living organisms, other forms of fermentation can occur.
[src:glucose/glucose] The bacterium *Escherichia coli* can grow on nutrient media containing glucose as the sole carbon source.
[src:glucose/glucose] In some bacteria and, in modified form, also in archaea, glucose is degraded via the Entner-Doudoroff pathway.
[src:glucose/glucose] With glucose, a mechanism for gene regulation was discovered in *E. coli*, the catabolite repression (formerly known as *glucose effect*).
[src:glucose/glucose] Use of glucose as an energy source in cells is by either aerobic respiration, anaerobic respiration, or fermentation.
[src:glucose/glucose] The first step of glycolysis is the phosphorylation of glucose by a hexokinase to form glucose 6-phosphate.
[src:glucose/glucose] The main reason for the immediate phosphorylation of glucose is to prevent its diffusion out of the cell as the charged phosphate group prevents glucose 6-phosphate from easily crossing the cell membrane.
[src:glucose/glucose] Furthermore, addition of the high-energy phosphate group activates glucose for subsequent breakdown in later steps of glycolysis.
[src:glucose/glucose] In anaerobic respiration, one glucose molecule produces a net gain of two ATP molecules (four ATP molecules are produced during glycolysis through substrate-level phosphorylation, but two are required by enzymes used during the process).
[src:glucose/glucose] In aerobic respiration, a molecule of glucose is much more profitable in that a maximum net production of 30 or 32 ATP molecules (depending on the organism) is generated.
[src:glucose/glucose] Tumor cells often grow comparatively quickly and consume an above-average amount of glucose by glycolysis, which leads to the formation of lactate, the end product of fermentation in mammals, even in the presence of oxygen.
[src:glucose/glucose] For the increased uptake of glucose in tumors various SGLT and GLUT are overly produced.
[src:glucose/glucose] In yeast, ethanol is fermented at high glucose concentrations, even in the presence of oxygen (which normally leads to respiration rather than fermentation).
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose can also degrade to form carbon dioxide through abiotic means.
[src:glucose/glucose] This has been demonstrated to occur experimentally via oxidation and hydrolysis at 22 °C and a pH of 2.5.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose is a ubiquitous fuel in biology.
[src:glucose/glucose] It is used as an energy source in organisms, from bacteria to humans, through either aerobic respiration, anaerobic respiration (in bacteria), or fermentation.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose is the human body's key source of energy, through aerobic respiration, providing about 3.75 kilocalories (16 kilojoules) of food energy per gram.
[src:glucose/glucose] Breakdown of carbohydrates (e.g., starch) yields mono- and disaccharides, most of which is glucose.
[src:glucose/glucose] Through glycolysis and later in the reactions of the citric acid cycle and oxidative phosphorylation, glucose is oxidized to eventually form carbon dioxide and water, yielding energy mostly in the form of adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:glucose/glucose] The insulin reaction, and other mechanisms, regulate the concentration of glucose in the blood.
[src:glucose/glucose] The physiological caloric value of glucose, depending on the source, is 16.2 kilojoules per gram or 15.7 kJ/g (3.74 kcal/g).
[src:glucose/glucose] The high availability of carbohydrates from plant biomass has led to a variety of methods during evolution, especially in microorganisms, to utilize glucose for energy and carbon storage.
[src:glucose/glucose] Differences exist in which end product can no longer be used for energy production.
[src:glucose/glucose] The presence of individual genes, and their gene products, the enzymes, determine which reactions are possible.
[src:glucose/glucose] The metabolic pathway of glycolysis is used by almost all living beings.
[src:glucose/glucose] An essential difference in the use of glycolysis is the recovery of NADPH as a reductant for anabolism that would otherwise have to be generated indirectly.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose and oxygen supply almost all the energy for the brain, so its availability influences psychological processes.
[src:glucose/glucose] When glucose is low, psychological processes requiring mental effort (e.g., self-control, effortful decision-making) are impaired.
[src:glucose/glucose] In the brain, which is dependent on glucose and oxygen as the major source of energy, the glucose concentration is usually 4 to 6 mM (5 mM equals 90 mg/dL), but decreases to 2 to 3 mM when fasting.
[src:glucose/glucose] Confusion occurs below 1 mM and coma at lower levels.
[src:glucose/glucose] The glucose in the blood is called blood sugar.
[src:glucose/glucose] Blood sugar levels are regulated by glucose-binding nerve cells in the hypothalamus.
[src:glucose/glucose] In addition, glucose in the brain binds to glucose receptors of the reward system in the nucleus accumbens.
[src:glucose/glucose] The binding of glucose to the sweet receptor on the tongue induces a release of various hormones of energy metabolism, either through glucose or through other sugars, leading to an increased cellular uptake and lower blood sugar levels.
[src:glucose/glucose] Artificial sweeteners do not lower blood sugar levels.
[src:glucose/glucose] The blood sugar content of a healthy person in the short-time fasting state, e.g. after overnight fasting, is about 70 to 100 mg/dL of blood (4 to 5.5 mM).
[src:glucose/glucose] In blood plasma, the measured values are about 10–15% higher.
[src:glucose/glucose] In addition, the values in the arterial blood are higher than the concentrations in the venous blood since glucose is absorbed into the tissue during the passage of the capillary bed.
[src:glucose/glucose] Also in the capillary blood, which is often used for blood sugar determination, the values are sometimes higher than in the venous blood.
[src:glucose/glucose] The glucose content of the blood is regulated by the hormones insulin, incretin, and glucagon.
[src:glucose/glucose] Insulin lowers the glucose level, glucagon increases it.
[src:glucose/glucose] Furthermore, the hormones adrenaline, thyroxine, glucocorticoids, somatotropin, and adrenocorticotropin lead to an increase in the glucose level.
[src:glucose/glucose] There is also a hormone-independent regulation, which is referred to as glucose autoregulation.
[src:glucose/glucose] After food intake the blood sugar concentration increases.
[src:glucose/glucose] Values over 180 mg/dL in venous whole blood are pathological and are termed hyperglycemia, values below 40 mg/dL are termed hypoglycaemia.
[src:glucose/glucose] When needed, glucose is released into the bloodstream by glucose-6-phosphatase from glucose-6-phosphate originating from liver and kidney glycogen, thereby regulating the homeostasis of blood glucose concentration.
[src:glucose/glucose] In ruminants, the blood glucose concentration is lower (60 mg/dL in cattle and 40 mg/dL in sheep), because the carbohydrates are converted more by their gut microbiota into short-chain fatty acids.
[src:glucose/glucose] Liver cell glycogen can be converted to glucose and returned to the blood when insulin is low or absent; muscle cell glycogen is not returned to the blood because of a lack of enzymes.
[src:glucose/glucose] In fat cells, glucose is used to power reactions that synthesize some fat types and have other purposes.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glycogen is the body's "glucose energy storage" mechanism, because it is much more "space efficient" and less reactive than glucose itself.
[src:glucose/glucose] As a result of its importance in human health, glucose is an analyte in glucose tests that are common medical blood tests.
[src:glucose/glucose] Eating or fasting prior to taking a blood sample has an effect on analyses for glucose in the blood; a high fasting glucose blood sugar level may be a sign of prediabetes or diabetes mellitus.
[src:glucose/glucose] The glycemic index is an indicator of the speed of resorption and conversion to blood glucose levels from ingested carbohydrates, measured as the area under the curve of blood glucose levels after consumption in comparison to glucose (glucose is defined as 100).
[src:glucose/glucose] The clinical importance of the glycemic index is controversial, as foods with high fat contents slow the resorption of carbohydrates and lower the glycemic index, e.g. ice cream.
[src:glucose/glucose] An alternative indicator is the insulin index, measured as the impact of carbohydrate consumption on the blood insulin levels.
[src:glucose/glucose] The glycemic load is an indicator for the amount of glucose added to blood glucose levels after consumption, based on the glycemic index and the amount of consumed food.
[src:glucose/glucose] Organisms use glucose as a precursor for the synthesis of several important substances.
[src:glucose/glucose] Starch, cellulose, and glycogen ("animal starch") are common glucose polymers (polysaccharides).
[src:glucose/glucose] Some of these polymers (starch or glycogen) serve as energy stores, while others (cellulose and chitin, which is made from a derivative of glucose) have structural roles.
[src:glucose/glucose] Oligosaccharides of glucose combined with other sugars serve as important energy stores.
[src:glucose/glucose] These include lactose, the predominant sugar in milk, which is a glucose-galactose disaccharide, and sucrose, another disaccharide, which is composed of glucose and fructose.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose is also added onto certain proteins and lipids in a process called glycosylation.
[src:glucose/glucose] This is often critical for their functioning.
[src:glucose/glucose] The enzymes that join glucose to other molecules usually use phosphorylated glucose to power the formation of the new bond by coupling it with the breaking of the glucose-phosphate bond.
[src:glucose/glucose] Other than its direct use as a monomer, glucose can be broken down to synthesize a wide variety of other biomolecules.
[src:glucose/glucose] This is important, as glucose serves both as a primary store of energy and as a source of organic carbon.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose can be broken down and converted into lipids.
[src:glucose/glucose] It is also a precursor for the synthesis of other important molecules such as vitamin C (ascorbic acid).
[src:glucose/glucose] In living organisms, glucose is converted to several other chemical compounds that are the starting material for various metabolic pathways.
[src:glucose/glucose] Among them, all other monosaccharides, such as fructose (via the polyol pathway), mannose (the epimer of glucose at position 2), galactose (the epimer at position 4), fucose, various uronic acids, and the amino sugars are produced from glucose.
[src:glucose/glucose] In addition to the phosphorylation to glucose-6-phosphate, which is part of the glycolysis, glucose can be oxidized during its degradation to glucono-1,5-lactone.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose is used in some bacteria as a building block in the trehalose or the dextran biosynthesis and in animals as a building block of glycogen.
[src:glucose/glucose] Glucose can also be converted from bacterial xylose isomerase to fructose.
[src:glucose/glucose] In addition, glucose metabolites produce all nonessential amino acids, sugar alcohols such as mannitol and sorbitol, fatty acids, cholesterol, and nucleic acids.
[src:glucose/glucose] Finally, glucose is used as a building block in the glycosylation of proteins to glycoproteins, glycolipids, peptidoglycans, glycosides, and other substances (catalyzed by glycosyltransferases) and can be cleaved from them by glycosidases.
[src:glucose/glucose] In addition to its well-known function as a cellular energy source, glucose has been identified as a master regulator of tissue maturation.
[src:glucose/glucose] A 2025 study by Stanford Medicine uncovered that glucose, in its intact (non-metabolized) form, can bind to various regulatory proteins involved in gene expression.
[src:glucose/glucose] One such protein is IRF6, which alters its conformation upon glucose binding, thereby influencing the expression of genes associated with stem cell differentiation.
[src:glucose/glucose] This regulatory role is independent of glucose's catabolic function and has been observed across multiple tissue types, including skin, bone, fat, and white blood cells.
[src:glucose/glucose] The research demonstrated that even glucose analogs incapable of metabolism could promote differentiation, suggesting a signaling function for glucose.
[src:glucose/glucose] These findings have potential implications in understanding and treating diseases characterized by impaired differentiation, such as diabetes and certain cancers.
[src:glucose/glucose] Diabetes is a metabolic disorder where the body is unable to regulate levels of glucose in the blood either because of a lack of insulin in the body or the failure, by cells in the body, to respond properly to insulin.
[src:glucose/glucose] Each of these situations can be caused by persistently high elevations of blood glucose levels, through pancreatic burnout and insulin resistance.
[src:glucose/glucose] The pancreas is the organ responsible for the secretion of the hormones insulin and glucagon.
[src:glucose/glucose] Insulin is a hormone that regulates glucose levels, allowing the body's cells to absorb and use glucose.
[src:glucose/glucose] Without it, glucose cannot enter the cell and therefore cannot be used as fuel for the body's functions.
[src:glucose/glucose] If the pancreas is exposed to persistently high elevations of blood glucose levels, the insulin-producing cells in the pancreas could be damaged, causing a lack of insulin in the body.
[src:glucose/glucose] Insulin resistance occurs when the pancreas tries to produce more and more insulin in response to persistently elevated blood glucose levels.
[src:glucose/glucose] Eventually, the rest of the body becomes resistant to the insulin that the pancreas is producing, thereby requiring more insulin to achieve the same blood glucose-lowering effect, and forcing the pancreas to produce even more insulin to compete with the resistance.
[src:glucose/glucose] This negative spiral contributes to pancreatic burnout, and the disease progression of diabetes.
[src:glucose/glucose] To monitor the body's response to blood glucose-lowering therapy, glucose levels can be measured.
[src:glucose/glucose] Blood glucose monitoring can be performed by multiple methods, such as the fasting glucose test which measures the level of glucose in the blood after 8 hours of fasting.
[src:glucose/glucose] Another test is the 2-hour glucose tolerance test (GTT) – for this test, the person has a fasting glucose test done, then drinks a 75-gram glucose drink and is retested.
[src:glucose/glucose] This test measures the ability of the person's body to process glucose.
[src:glucose/glucose] Over time the blood glucose levels should decrease as insulin allows it to be taken up by cells and exit the blood stream.
[src:glucose/glucose] Hypoglycemia is a condition that occurs when blood glucose levels decrease below normal, causing symptoms including anxiety, tremors, nausea, palpitations, confusion, and coma.
[src:glucose/glucose] Individuals with diabetes or other conditions that result in low blood sugar may carry glucose tablets, oral glucose gel, hard candy, or sugar packets to use when their blood sugar becomes too low.
[src:glucose/glucose] Severe low blood sugar can lead to confusion, coma, neurological damage and other potentially serious complications, making it unsafe to administer glucose by mouth.
[src:glucose/glucose] In these cases, dextrose (D-glucose) can be administered into a vein to quickly and directly raise blood glucose levels.
[src:glucose/ose] The suffix ***-ose*** (/oʊz, oʊs/) is used in organic chemistry to form the names of sugars.
[src:glucose/ose] This Latin suffix means "full of", "abounding in", "given to", or "like".
[src:glucose/ose] Numerous systems exist to name specific sugars more descriptively.
[src:glucose/ose] The suffix is also used more generally in English to form adjectives from nouns, with the sense "full of", as in "verbose": wordy, full of words.
[src:glucose/ose] Monosaccharides, the simplest sugars, may be named according to the number of carbon atoms in each molecule of the sugar: pentose is a five-carbon monosaccharide, and hexose is a six-carbon monosaccharide.
[src:glucose/ose] Aldehyde monosaccharides may be called aldoses; ketone monosaccharides may be called ketoses.
[src:glucose/ose] Larger sugars such as disaccharides and polysaccharides can be named to reflect their qualities.
[src:glucose/ose] Lactose, a disaccharide found in milk, gets its name from the Latin word for milk combined with the sugar suffix; its name means "milk sugar".
[src:glucose/ose] The polysaccharide that makes up plant starch is named amylose, or "starch sugar"; see amyl.
[src:glucose/ose] Derived from sucrose, whose name came from Latin *sucrum* = "sugar" plus the common Latin adjective-forming suffix *-ōsus*; Latin *sucrosus* would mean "sugary".
